5000|$|In public {{international}} law, clausula rebus sic stantibus (Latin for [...] "things thus standing") is {{the legal}} doctrine allowing for treaties to become inapplicable because of a <b>fundamental</b> <b>change</b> <b>of</b> <b>circumstances.</b> It is essentially an [...] "escape clause" [...] that makes {{an exception to the}} general rule of pacta sunt servanda (promises must be kept).|$|E
