5000|$|The {{doctrine}} {{is part of}} customary international law, but is also provided for in the 1969 Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties under Article 62 (<b>Fundamental</b> <b>Change</b> <b>of</b> <b>Circumstance),</b> although the {{doctrine is}} never mentioned by name. Article 62 provides the only two justifications of the invocation of rebus sic stantibus: first, that the circumstances existing {{at the time of}} the conclusion of the treaty were indeed objectively essential to the obligations of treaty (sub-paragraph A) and the instance wherein the <b>change</b> <b>of</b> <b>circumstances</b> has had a radical effect on the obligations of the treaty (sub-paragraph B).|$|R
